---
layout: article
title: Start with Sign in with Appwrite
description: Register an app and run the full Sign in with Appwrite flow, from consent screen to your first authorized API call.
back: /docs/partners/apps
---

This guide builds Sign in with Appwrite into an app, start to finish. The running example is Horizon, a deployment dashboard: a user clicks its sign-in button, approves access on the Appwrite consent screen, and Horizon reads their projects with the tokens it receives. By the end, you will have run the same journey with your own app.

You need a server that can receive a redirect and keep a client secret. The examples use `http://localhost:7700/oauth/callback` as the redirect URI; replace it with your own.

# Register your app {% #register %}

{% only_dark %}
![Marketplace tab of an organization with the Add app action](/images/docs/partners/apps/dark/registration-marketplace.avif)
{% /only_dark %}
{% only_light %}
![Marketplace tab of an organization with the Add app action](/images/docs/partners/apps/registration-marketplace.avif)
{% /only_light %}

Before Appwrite can show your app to anyone, it needs to know the app exists. In the Console, open your organization's **Marketplace** tab and click **Add app**. Give it a name, a slug, a category, and a short description; the slug becomes your client ID, so Horizon signs in as `horizon`.

{% only_dark %}
![OAuth client page with client type and redirect URIs](/images/docs/partners/apps/dark/registration-oauth-client.avif)
{% /only_dark %}
{% only_light %}
![OAuth client page with client type and redirect URIs](/images/docs/partners/apps/registration-oauth-client.avif)
{% /only_light %}

The new app opens on its settings pages. On **OAuth client**, keep the type **Confidential**, since your server will hold a secret, and add your redirect URI to the list. The authorization endpoint refuses to send users anywhere else, which is what makes the callback trustworthy.

{% only_dark %}
![OAuth secrets page with active secrets](/images/docs/partners/apps/dark/registration-secrets.avif)
{% /only_dark %}
{% only_light %}
![OAuth secrets page with active secrets](/images/docs/partners/apps/registration-secrets.avif)
{% /only_light %}

Last, your app needs a way to prove it is really Horizon when it exchanges codes for tokens. On **OAuth secrets**, select **Create secret** and copy the value; it is shown once. Store the client ID and the secret in your server's environment.

The same registration works from code with the `apps` service, which is how you would script it in CI or offer it inside your own product:

{% multicode %}
```server-nodejs
import { Client, Apps, ID } from 'node-appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('console')
    .setSession(''); // Your Appwrite account session

const apps = new Apps(client);

const app = await apps.create({
    appId: ID.unique(),
    name: 'Horizon',
    redirectUris: ['http://localhost:7700/oauth/callback'],
    type: 'confidential'
});

const secret = await apps.createSecret({ appId: app.$id });
```

```server-deno
import { Client, Apps, ID } from 'npm:node-appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
