```server-go
package main

import (
    "fmt"

    "github.com/appwrite/sdk-for-go/apps"
    "github.com/appwrite/sdk-for-go/client"
    "github.com/appwrite/sdk-for-go/id"
)

func main() {
    c := client.New(
        client.WithEndpoint("https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1"),
        client.WithProject("console"),
        client.WithSession(""), // Your Appwrite account session
    )

    service := apps.New(c)

    app, err := service.Create(
        id.Unique(),
        "Horizon",
        []string{"http://localhost:7700/oauth/callback"},
        apps.WithCreateType("confidential"),
    )
    if err != nil {
        panic(err)
    }

    secret, err := service.CreateSecret(app.Id)
    if err != nil {
        panic(err)
    }

    fmt.Println(secret)
}
```

```server-rust
use appwrite::Client;
use appwrite::id::ID;
use appwrite::services::Apps;

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    let client = Client::new();
    client.set_endpoint("https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1");
    client.set_project("console");
    client.set_session(""); // Your Appwrite account session

    let apps = Apps::new(&client);

    let app = apps.create(
        &ID::unique(),
        "Horizon",
        vec!["http://localhost:7700/oauth/callback"],
        None, None, None, None, None, None, None, None, None, None, None, None, None,
        Some("confidential"),
        None, None,
    ).await?;

    let secret = apps.create_secret(&app.id).await?;
    println!("{}", secret.secret); // Shown only once

    Ok(())
}
```
{% /multicode %}

[Registration](/docs/partners/apps/registration) covers both paths in detail.

# Redirect the user {% #redirect %}

With credentials in your environment, Horizon can offer its sign-in button. The button sends the user to the authorization endpoint, and the query string carries everything your app asks for: identity scopes, one project scope, and an `authorization_details` parameter that lets the user pick which projects the grant applies to.

```text
https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1/oauth2/console/authorize
  ?client_id=<CLIENT_ID>
  &redirect_uri=http://localhost:7700/oauth/callback
  &response_type=code
  &scope=openid profile email project:databases.read
  &state=<RANDOM_STATE>
  &authorization_details=[{"type":"project","identifiers":["*"]}]
```

URL-encode the values. Generate a fresh random `state` per request and verify it on the way back; it is your protection against forged callbacks. The wildcard identifier asks for any project, which the consent screen turns into a picker the user controls. Scopes are described in the [scope catalog](/docs/partners/apps/scopes).

# User grants access {% #consent %}

{% only_dark %}
![Consent screen asking to authorize the app with selected projects](/images/docs/partners/apps/dark/quick-start-consent.avif)
{% /only_dark %}
{% only_light %}
![Consent screen asking to authorize the app with selected projects](/images/docs/partners/apps/quick-start-consent.avif)
{% /only_light %}

This is the moment the user meets your app inside Appwrite. The consent screen shows Horizon's name and logo, lists each requested permission in plain language, and lets the user select the projects the grant covers or reduce the access to read-only. On approval, the browser returns to your redirect URI:

```text
http://localhost:7700/oauth/callback?code=<CODE>&state=<RANDOM_STATE>&iss=https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1/oauth2/console
```

Verify that `state` matches what you sent, then use the code within five minutes. It is single-use.

# Exchange the code {% #exchange %}

From your server, exchange the code for tokens. Authenticate with your client credentials over HTTP basic auth.

{% multicode %}
```curl
curl -X POST https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1/oauth2/console/token \
  -u "<CLIENT_ID>:<CLIENT_SECRET>" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded" \
  -d "grant_type=authorization_code" \
  -d "code=<CODE>" \
  -d "redirect_uri=http://localhost:7700/oauth/callback"
```

```hurl
POST https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1/oauth2/console/token
[BasicAuth]
<CLIENT_ID>: <CLIENT_SECRET>
[Form]
grant_type: authorization_code
code: <CODE>
redirect_uri: http://localhost:7700/oauth/callback
```
{% /multicode %}

The response carries the three tokens and echoes what the user actually granted:

```json
{
  "access_token": "eyJ0eXAiOiJhdCtqd3QiLCJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiJ9...",
  "token_type": "Bearer",
  "expires_in": 28800,
  "refresh_token": "eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9...",
  "scope": "openid profile email project:databases.read",
  "authorization_details": [{ "type": "project", "identifiers": ["*"] }],
  "id_token": "eyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiJ9..."
}
```

Compare `scope` and `authorization_details` against what you requested; the user may have granted less. Store the refresh token like a password. [Tokens](/docs/partners/apps/tokens) covers lifetimes, refresh rotation, and revocation.

# List the user's projects {% #list-projects %}

The user is signed in and Horizon holds its tokens. Now the payoff: every Sign in with Appwrite token can list the projects and organizations it was granted. Pass the access token as a bearer token with any Appwrite Server SDK.

{% multicode %}
```server-nodejs
import { Client, Oauth2 } from 'node-appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('console')
    .setBearer('Bearer <ACCESS_TOKEN>'); // The user's access token

const oauth2 = new Oauth2(client);

const projects = await oauth2.listProjects();
```

```server-deno
import { Client, Oauth2 } from 'npm:node-appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('console')
    .setBearer('Bearer <ACCESS_TOKEN>'); // The user's access token

const oauth2 = new Oauth2(client);

const projects = await oauth2.listProjects();
```

```server-python
from appwrite.client import Client
from appwrite.services.oauth2 import Oauth2

client = Client()
client.set_endpoint('https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
client.set_project('console')
client.set_bearer('Bearer <ACCESS_TOKEN>')  # The user's access token

oauth2 = Oauth2(client)

projects = oauth2.list_projects()
```

